amd64_hacker:

Further review of the proposal.  Anything in brackets is my suggested 
alteration or addition:

1.  What is QuikScript? sec, 2d par. begins: &quot;QuikScript has 40 [44] 
letters, of which 40 are core letters,...&quot;

2.  This would no doubt have been caught:  new typo in Alternate Forms 
sec., 3d par. &quot;height&quot; mispelled - &quot;e&quot; missing.

3.  My suspicion is that the upper half of S-ee could easily be misread 
as an H-e or even a T-ea, if one&#39;s handwriting is sloppy or hurried. 

I have sat here trying Ch-eer as a half-height, and I don&#39;t care for 
it.  After the initial hook, the pen-stroke is moving from right to left 
as it descends and going from that directly into a vowel starting at the 
center writing line just doesn&#39;t seem to work very well to me.

I am comfortable with Y-e and Wh-y as half-heights since either of these 
half-letters clearly cannot be anything else.

4.  Text of Alternate Forms sec. -- Should our desire to have the 
half-height and alternate forms available be explained more 
effectively?  If our proposal states that their primary purpose is to 
increase the speed of handwriting, the powers that be in Unicode may 
feel these variants serve little purpose in computer-generated text.

In fact, I believe the half-height letters, as well as the alternate 
forms, will not only aid writing speed, but assist adept readers in 
reading faster since they produce more distinctive word-scapes as the 
eye scans along the lines. 

5.  Variant Selectors -- can you explain how this would work?  From what 
you have written, it seems that the font would normally select whether a 
full letter or a half-letter or an alternate form would be used in a 
given context?  Is that correct?  If so, how is that programmed into the 
font?  For example, would the font know which form of &quot;n&quot; to use based 
on what letter precedes it?

Previously, we have mapped these alternate forms and half height letters 
on to the keyboard so that we could choose when we wanted to use them.  
My ignorance of how Unicode functions leaves me unclear how having QS 
encoded in Unicode would change this.  Can you explain that?

I take it that the purpose of the variant selectors was to allow us to 
override the font&#39;s programming if it was needed.  Correct?   But now 
that seems unnecessary to you.  Does that mean that you believe that 
having the flexibility to make the choice of half-letters or alternate 
forms ourselves doesn&#39;t seem important to try to include that in the 
proposal?  Or you just believe the Unicode people, for some reason, 
would not want that in the encoding of QS?

Paige


